comment:
Six o'clock already
I was just in the middle of a dream
I was kissin' Valentino
By a crystal-blue, Italian stream
But I can't be late
'Cause then I guess I just won't get paid
These are the days
When you wish your bed was already made
It's just another manic Monday (Woah, woah)
I wish it was Sunday (Woah, woah)
'Cause that's my fun day (Woah, woah, woah, woah)
My I don't have to run day (Woah, woah)
It's just another manic Monday
Have to catch an early train
Got to be to work by nine
And if I had an aeroplane
I still couldn't make it on time
'Cause it takes me so long (Oh, oh)
Just to figure out what I'm gonna wear
Blame it on the train
But the boss is already there
It's just another manic Monday (Woah, woah)
I wish it was Sunday (Woah, woah)
'Cause that's my fun day (Woah, woah, woah, woah)
My I don't have to run day (Woah, woah)
It's just another manic Monday
Of all my nights
Why did my lover have to pick last night
To get down?
(Last night, last night)
Doesn't it matter
That I have to feed the both of us?
Employment's down
He tells me in his bedroom voice
C'mon honey, let's go make some noise
Time it goes so fast
(When you're having fun)
It's just another manic Monday (Woah, woah)
I wish it was Sunday (Woah, woah)
'Cause that's my fun day (Woah, woah, woah, woah)

It's just another manic Monday (Woah, woah)

'Cause that's my fun day (Woah, woah)
It's just another manic Monday

comment:
The lyrics of this song is so timeless, and relatable.  I remembered when I used to struggle to find employment, and my boyfriend at the time, constantly threatened to kick me out for not financially contributing.  Mind you, I cooked, cleaned, ran errands, had dinner, and a BJ waiting for him every night when he got off work, so I was still contributing.  

Soon as I started working at the nursing home as a housekeeper, I was too exhausted to do any housework in between my shifts, my bf and I had delivery more often rather than cook at home.  I had to do chores on my days off, my feet ached too much to go out anywhere anyway.  My bf would often get mad at me for not giving him some on a worknight.  I'd be like "Hey, this is what you wanted.  I'm too tired, you only get 2 days a week from now on, on my days off.  I got work tomorrow, goodnight."  lol

Six o'clock already

When you wish your bed was already made

'Cause that's my fun day
My "I don't have to run" day

Have to catch an early train
Got to be to work by nine
And if I had an airplane

It's just another manic Monday
Wish it was Sunday

My "I don't have to run" day

All of my nights
Why did my lover have to pick last night

That I have to feed the both of us
Employment's down
He tells me in his bedroom voice

It's just another manic Monday

But the boss is already there

Why did my lover have to pick last night
To get down
Doesn't it matter

Employment's down

C'mon honey, let's go make some noise
Time it goes so fast
When you're having fun

All the old paintings on the tomb
They do the sand dance, don't you know?
If they move too quick (oh-way-oh)
They're falling down like a domino

All the bazaar men by the Nile
They got the money on a bet
Gold crocodiles (oh-way-oh)
They snap their teeth on your cigarette

Foreign types with the hookah pipes say
(Way-oh-way-oh, ooh-way-oh-way-oh)
Walk like an Egyptian

[Verse 2: Michael Steele]
The blonde waitresses take their trays
They spin around and they cross the floor
They've got the moves (oh-way-oh)
You drop your drink, then they bring you more

All the school kids so sick of books
They like the punk and the metal band
When the buzzer rings (oh-way-oh)
They're walking like an Egyptian

All the kids in the marketplace say
(Way-oh-way-oh, ooh-way-oh-way-oh)
Walk like an Egyptian

[Verse 3: Susanna Hoffs]
Slide your feet up the street, bend your back
Shift your arm, then you pull it back
Life is hard you know (oh-way-oh)
So strike a pose on a Cadillac

If you want to find all the cops
They're hanging out in the donut shop
They sing and dance (oh-way-oh)
They spin the clubs, cruise down the block

comment: I have a lot to say about this song. My dad played it constantly when I was a kid. (I’m a millennial born in the early 90’s). I remember laying in bed watching my mom get ready for work and feeling like this song was about her. It seemed so distant at the time and I didn’t know what a lot of the words meant. Here I am at 26 with a full time job and this is basically a weekly feeling lol. To this day I really don’t think I’ve heard this song anywhere else other than coming out of the speakers of my Dad’s grand prix😂 Anyways, I don’t usually post on YouTube or anywhere really but take care friends glad to see y’all enjoying these classic bangers. God bless :)

I remember this song. My ex boyfriend Simon Theo Johnson said I just looked like Susannah, the lead singer of this group. I got grounded for over 2 months for seeing this boy and taking me to Halifax to his house instead of going to youth club. He was 5 years too old for me and kept pestering me to go out with him when I was in the chorus line of Mother Goose. Eventually I gave in to his demand to go out with me after his several failed attempts to ask me out. 

I wondered why a customer Firth pollard was getting distressed when I spoke about the subject to another customer Rex the dinosaur? I had no clue or idea what happened to him after 1985!!! I moved on and started dating Steve Parrish. 🤷🏻‍♀️✌️🤷🏻‍♀️🤷🏻‍♀️🤷🏻‍♀️🤷🏻‍♀️🤕😩🧘‍♀️

comment:
Did Prince wrote Manic Monday for the bangles?

Prince wrote "Manic Monday" in 1984, and recorded it as a duet for the band Apollonia 6's self-titled album; however, he eventually pulled the song. 

Two years later, he offered the single to The Bangles under the pseudonym "Christopher", a character he played in the 1986 film Under the Cherry Moon.

comment:
💜Did you see Prince's EYE at the very beginning of the video!!! The original version of this song on Prince's album The Originals is only a demo ( demonstration) that he made so that the singer can follow how to perform the song. That's why this is a more polished version and Prince's version is a little rougher. Prince does play the keyboards and the synthesizer on The Bangles version too. 
              This song was originally written for the group Apollonia 6 to go on their debut album. But Prince believe that The Bangles would be able to perform it better and give the song some longevity. The same thing he did with the song The Glamorous Life. That was written about Apollonia or Vanity. But once again Prince gave it to an artist he felt could present the song better. Sheila E could not only sing it, she could  perform the procussions while she's doing it. Two smart choices on Prince's part.💜

comment: Ladies, I know your older now and unfortunately no longer touring, but I Wish to thank you for your Music and in my Mind, You Gals were the Best. You instilled a Spirit of Music Passion, Sexy Fun, and Positive energy that made me Smile, I would sing and dance to your Songs, and I will never forget You gals. You enriched my Life, inspired Me to Sing and play Guitar in a Band for over 10 yrs, it wasnt easy for me, I had terrible stage fright that first year of gigs, I was Pretty, I could Sing well and play many Guitars, but I was so Shy, watching all those eyes judging me, it took awhile for me to become comfortable and watching your Music Videos helped me so much. TYSVM

comment:
80's women  >  Modern women


I wasn't quite old enough to enjoy the 80's but I damn sure enjoyed the 90's. Kids today just don't understand how much different it was. As useful as the internet and smartphones are, not having them back then really helped you to be free. You weren't at home getting online, texting people or playing games. You went out with friends and ran all over the place having fun and meeting girls and there were far more people out looking to have fun. It was incredible. Today there are not near as many people out and there is so much traffic everywhere that  you can't enjoy riding around town meeting girls the way you could back then. Definitely the best times of my life.

comment:
When this was in the charts, I was a 20 something-year-old signing on the dole under Maggie Thatcher and the Tories in the UK, part of it was because jobs were harder to get back then and part of it was because I decided that the whole system sucked and if I got a job I would become a part of that system, so I was happy to stay unemployed, although I made some token efforts to look for work as the dole office required me to.

Of course, I've done some growing up since then lol and I have had loads of jobs and work now even though I'll be 55 this year, but deep down, I still have that same ideology as I did back then, it's just that I keep it to myself, this song, in some ways, has that same undertone of her quietly questioning herself, wishing her life was different, wanting to run away from reality and even though she had a job, she was wondering why she was bothering to get up in the morning because it was a road to nowhere and I could relate to that even back then and still do today to a certain extent, that's why I remember this song and checked it out on Youtube :)

comment:
"Manic Monday"

Six o'clock already
I was just in the middle of a dream
I was kissin' Valentino
By a crystal blue Italian stream
But I can't be late
'Cause then I guess I just won't get paid
These are the days
When you wish your bed was already made

It's just another manic Monday
I wish it was Sunday
'Cause that's my fun day
My "I don't have to run" day
It's just another manic Monday

Have to catch an early train
Got to be to work by nine
And if I had an airplane
I still couldn't make it on time
'Cause it takes me so long just to figure out
What I'm gonna wear
Blame it on the train
But the boss is already there

It's just another manic Monday
Wish it was Sunday
'Cause that's my fun day
My "I don't have to run" day
It's just another manic Monday

All of my nights
Why did my lover have to pick last night
To get down?
(Last night, last night)
Doesn't it matter
That I have to feed the both of us
Employment's down
He tells me in his bedroom voice
"C'mon honey, let's go make some noise"
Time it goes so fast
(When you're having fun)

It's just another manic Monday
I wish it was Sunday
'Cause that's my fun day
"I don't have to run" day

It's just another manic Monday
I wish it was Sunday
'Cause that's my fun day
It's just a manic Monday

comment:
Parmadale Orphanage and it’s 13 cottages, Church, school and gymnasium is mostly demolished as are the hopes of millions of people’s lives being saved by a series of TV shows I promoted for 20 months called Parmadale’s Resurrection where pet therapy would have dramatized the healing of human suffering.  Where 5% of advertising profits would have gone to the City of Parma, 5% would have gone to the Parma City School District and the rest would have gone to animal welfare organizations and the humanitarian suffering each of the cottages’ shows would have dealt with.

Had Parmadale been given to me, there isn’t a TV executive in the world who would have not fought for the broadcast rights. The narration and merits were explained to virtually all Parma residents in over a hundred facebook posts.
 
 
The Parmadale’s Resurrection shows would have raised $234 million yearly, nearly forever to the City of Parma and school board  so it could have provided funding to  fix it’s sewers which causes flooding for 10,000 of it’s 32,000 homes which makes them unhealthy to live in, depilated roads and countless school problems including having no air conditioning and so few facilities they frequently have to close schools, leaving 6,000 students of low income parents who have to either miss work or pay for a baby sitter to have to sacrifice their food budgets for the week. Along with so many problems that Parma City School District is near the worst in the state of Ohio and probably no better on a national level.

Parma had a chance to solve all their problems and have financial stability forever without having to spend a single tax dollar ever, nor take any tax payer grant money from any other organization, while turning a network called ION Life(with Jewel’s show at 3, Dr. Oz at 4, Anna and Kristina at 5, then millions of viewers watching cats and dogs heal human suffering until 11)  into a major network for only a few million dollars for broadcast rights and intellectual property rights for social cause TV.  Parma could have had the most beautiful perfect entity ever incarnated, equaling We Are the World’s humanitarian fund raising over the last 33 years in but PR’s first 4 months. 

The city of Parma had no concern for the world even if they themselves could be helped. The world should give nothing to Parma. 
 
Parmadale’s Resurrection would have also raised nearly $4 billion for the healing of human suffering, which could have saved the lives of 4 million people every year and started a copy cat nature of TV shows that I promoted as social cause TV that would have raised at least $500 billion for humanitarian benefit yearly forever. Hopefully, Parma’s barbaric atrocity will inspire facebookers and youtubers throughout the world to start similar shows in their hometowns using building in fear of demolition.
 
 
I appealed to Nicole Curtis(Rehab Addict star) many times from day one back to January of 2017. But the self-proclaimed goddess of goodness, self-proclaimed maker of heaven and earth and moral compass of the world decided instead to have her Season 8 be about some stupid Road 14 Mile home, then a season 9 home in her hometown. Neither of which had any significant historical effect. Yet, the most important place on earth for the healing of human suffering, whose ideals of love, care and compassion replacing electro shock therapy, water submersion and lobotomies lead to hundreds of millions of lives saved since 30,000 humanitarians came from throughout the world to Pamadale’s opening on January 23, 1925 wasn’t apparently important enough to even respond to.
 
 
But the most barbaric atrocity occurred when the owners of Parmadale, Parma Community Improvement Corporation with it’s board members Parma Mayor Tim Degeeter, Economic Development Director Erik Tollerup and Auditor Brian Day joined the most perverted relationship with the most needlessly superficial organization West Creek to spend $9 million to transform the area into basically a forest which according to grant proposals would have no economic or environmental benefit to Parma  nor anyone it the world at all.
 
 
Degeeter, Tollerup, Day, two private citizen board members of the PCIC and West Creek Conservancy  despite 410 pages of facebook postings over 20 months about the  documentation of Parmadale Resurrection’s merits, beautifully perfect business plans, made the most barbaric response possibly anyone has ever made. Just let millions of people die, so we can have our 40 acres more of parks.  The probable deaths of millions of people are the responsibility of Degeeter, Tollerup and Day and West Creek. I can only hope these national postings will inspire the nation to evolve social cause TV which can hopefully prevent those deaths Parma officials didn’t care about.
 
 
Even when Parma residents would have benefited tremendously, Degeeter, Tollerup and Day still turned their backs on their own residents.  It is beyond any level of human acceptability for the nation not to scorn Parma for turning their backs on the world’s suffering-for a park. For even despite that without Parmadale, there never would have been a Parma, Parma Heights or Seven Hills, 98% of facebook posts ridiculed PR, mostly on a faceook page “Meanwhile In Parma” and not until days before demolition did anyone voice a public opinion.  One last Parma ordinance 146-18 had a chance to save Parmadale. But not one city council member voted to have concern for humanity and not West Creek’s needless superficiality which now has an incalculable death toll. 
 
 
According to a Tollerup’s facebook like of my comment, not even if I had a TV contract in hand would Parmadale be saved, along with saving homeless people, AIDS patients, Leukemia, Cancer, Rape and Domestic Violence victims, Autism and Downs Syndrome people, and all the others the advertising profits would have provided direct aid, research funding, education, motivation and an endless list of ways in decades to come that pet therapy and the advertising profits would have saved millions of lives. Tollerup, Day, Degeeter and West Creek put more value in the grant’s proposal stated benefit as adding more area to kill deer, cats and bunny rabbits, then not just saving millions of lives even if they can save their own residents.

Hopefully, social cause TV will find cures for diseases saving millions, provide funding to help millions who would otherwise die, house the homeless, heal the suffering and save the lives of all the millions of people Parmadale could have saved if not burdened by being in Parma.
 
 
It’s absolutely unfathomable that the residents haven’t at the least called for them to resign and haven’t stopped supporting West Creek. During my tireless 20 month crusade not was there a single protest, demonstration, vigil or even one facebook posting by anyone other than me. 
 
One can only hope that this national tragedy and barbaric disregard for human life that Degeeter, Tollerup and Day joined together with West Creek Conservancy, can somehow serve as a martyr to having PR’s vision resurrected, even if 2,000 dumpsters are hauling away the debris to sit in landfills to sit for 20 years creating a huge massive ecological footprint from a supposed environmental organization.
 
 
The below video shows what West Creek did to a place that was relatively rehabable on August 2017 when they basically trashed the place like vandals and scavengers when it still looked like the Parmadale’s 90th Anniversary video.
 
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gPZuRwJKqds

comment:
Prince wrote this song when he was a kid. He was working in Dennys and he was pissed off 'cause he was late one Monday morning. He'd been up all night writing a hundred songs or so. He saw some chick in a Raspberry Beret walk in late at about half eleven, ten minutes after he got in, so that cheered him up a bit. 

At lunch time, he wrote a couple more songs.

comment:
I like the Bangles a lot and they had modest success, but when you look at the Billboard charts they did not write a lot of their hits.  For example, they only during their history had 8 top 40 hits and of those, only 2 were cowritten by Susanna Hoffs and one was a hit written solely by Debbie Peterson:
Walk Like An Egyptian - #1 - written by Liam Sternberg for The Bangles
Eternal Flame - #1 - written by Susanna Hoffs, Tom Kelly, and Billy Steinberg (who also played with Fleetwood Mac for a time)
Hazy Shade of Winter - #2 - written by Simon and Garfunkle, modified by the Bangles
Manic Monday - #2 - written by Prince for The Bangles
In Your Room - #5 - written by Susanna Hoffs, Tom Kelly, and Billy Steinberg

Walking Down Your Street - #11 - written by Susanna Hoffs, Louis Gutierrez, David Khane (produced for everyone including Paul McCartney, Sugar Ray, Kelly Clarkson, Tony Bennet, and many others)

If She Knew What She Wants - #29 - written by Jules Sheer
Be With You - #30 - written by Debbie Peterson 

I know they are talented - I know they were a great all female band in the 1980s and did reasonably well coming back in 2003, but I was shocked to learn that they really did not write any of the biggest hits we heard on the radio (knowing that Prince and Simon and Garfunkel were responsible for two of them).

comment: im going to explain music in a simple way, because ive realised what it is about these great songs of the 80s.   I will bet most people who love these songs like me were about 17-20 when it came out.  and this is when we are at most impressionable and create memories of first loves etc whilst driving around with these cassettes in our old cars.   yes kids we had cassettes we used to rewind to our favourite track.  or tape off the radio and we can all remember having to flip the cassette to get to the other good song on side B.   as we get older music doesn't create nostalgia so even if its good its got no connection. I can remember the day and who I was with the day I heard this song because I can do that with all 80s songs as I was young and it meant something as I knew id be at the record shop the weekend with my wages.      Today its really just not fun.  too sexual.

comment:
For those out there who really know the history of this song, there are two versions on the internet you probably have never heard.  The first is from Apollina 6 - the group Prince originally wrote the song for.  Didn't know there is a recorded demo version that definitely sounds like a different style from that original song?  Look here: https://www.bustle.com/articles/156448-theres-one-prince-song-that-you-probably-didnt-realize-he-wrote

Also on that web page is a version where Prince sang it with them on stage one time.  He sings the chorus and you definitely hear his voice, especially on the phrase "last night, last night."

comment:
I know Prince wrote this song. And it's amazing that he could think about the things a woman deals with like figuring out what to wear! Or how of all nights her lover gets there, and she stays up late to be with him.
Sorry, but even men have relationships with some women they will give up sleep to be with.   Yes, it's dysfunctional. But haven't we all been there at some point? 
This is what I love about music!  When someone else sings about the crazy emotions or even painful memories, it somehow is therapeutic to know you're not the only one who ever felt that way. 
The Bangles were such a talented all female band! 
The video is gorgeous and has clips of everyone in the band.  I love the sun-lit effect.

comment: Three ladies in this group, 2 sisters and another lady, I think.  One of them is Susanna Hoffs. This is bright and energetic, catchy stuff. Prince wrote for them too, and jumped on stage to play with them more than once!  And listen to the total clarity and pureness of the lead singer's voice..........wow!  Harmonies are great..........unlike many groups, they did the harmonies at the same time on the same track in the studio, not on separate tracks. Did you hear the interjected line, "C'mon honey, let's go make some noise!".....PRINCE's footprint!

comment:
Her er det budskab, der netop er blevet postet:
***************

--- Citat (Oprindeligt af Mads Hutters) ---
Da jeg var en lille dreng og i 1974-1975 mødte en dansk talende Alien når jeg blinkede i børnehave, der fortalte mig "for at komme tilbage til børnehave - du nødt til at gå ned korridoren og springe gennem hul i gulvet" Jeg gjorde det hurtigt og sad tilbage i chock. Et par dage senere kom halvt usynlige kvinde på min børnehave og sagde i dansk "Du er for gammel til at gå i børnehave og tog mig som en går ud døren jeg nye i en alder af 5-6 år, at min mor ikke kunne Forklar det til mig. jeg har glemt alt om det. 1989 jeg Becan at høre Voices grund af, hvad jeg i fortvivlelse forsøger at aldrig tænke over. jeg hørte den lokale Psyk og havde givet 600 piller som medicin til tre måneder. jeg var under uddannelse til Typo tech Titian og den dag jeg kom hjem havde jeg noget at spise, så jeg besluttede at spise alle de piller (Ikke en Suicide) .Næste dag jeg vågnede kom til Job 06:00 halv time senere fik jeg en gnist på min højre pegefinger og pludselig havde jeg en dårlig følelse som jeg kunne dø, hvis jeg blinkede og huskede, hvorfor det ikke var
sundt at spise alle dem Fluphenazin og så pludselig kom der et stjerneskud i vinduet foran mig og ud af vinduet bag mig igen chokeret over hvad der var sket, jeg bemærket Sun ændret farve til at være Neon par uger senere havde jeg til at dække min Windows, så jeg kunne ikke se Neon Sun og stoppede min uddannelse og igen forsøger at glemme begge ting, jeg lykkedes indtil 1999. så jeg drømmer jeg levede som dreng på hans familie 16-17 år i flere uger på samme drøm der opstod så den person herfra kommer til drømmen, og jeg stod på 2th sal, og det hele blev halvt synlige og noget (relateret til hullet i gulvet Monster) lidt mindre end en bowling terning kravlede på bagsiden af ​​drengen jeg drømte jeg var, og det kunne ikke stoppe efter mange gange ekstra det eksploderer i en hvid eksplosion og jeg kan lide kigget på hvid eksplosion bliver større og større fra ud af rummet par dage senere jeg drømmer jeg er den halve, der gik sine egne veje i Kindergarden han levede som udødelig som i
dungeons og drager i et sted, hvor de alle talte dansk der den kvinde, jeg husker talte til mig i Kinder have sagt jeg skulle rejse tilbage til her og dræber mig, mens jeg sover. Efter 5000 år I / han her kravlede gennem det åbne vindue så på "min" Computer blinke og lignende forsvandt, da han / jeg så mig selv i sengen jeg vågnede og chokeret. 2001 oplevede den evige Eksplosion næsten besvimede 2005 Jeg drømmer jeg er den udødelige spøgelse i en hvid verden intet andet Alt var hvidt og tiden gik som jeg ikke kunne vågne op efter 40 milliarder år, jeg / han overtog jeg så den evige Eksplosion ned gennem og jeg vågnede. 2011 Jeg drømte det sted den kvinde, jeg mødte i børnehave "Den Evige Dal" blev ramt af den stadigt voksende evige eksplosion ligesom varig 40 milliarder års torden da jeg huskede det hele og skrevet ned, hvad gør u antager skete?
--- End Quote ---
Rapporteret for at være en fantast. Hvide kitler job.
***************

comment:
Prince of course wrote this song. I think the reason he gave it to the Bangles is because the melody for the verses sounds just like the verse melody of his earlier song '1999'. 

So this song goes: 'Six o Clock already I was just in the middle of a dream...', and '1999' goes: 'I was dreaming when I wrote this, forgive me if it goes astray'. 

The melody is the same. If he'd sang both songs, people would have said he's ripping himself off. Giving 'Manic Monday' another group makes it one step removed.

comment: 1985;  recorded in the summer in LA, the LP was released late in '85/early '86 and four hit singles came from it.  Prince, under the pen name Christopher, wrote it (Controversy Music was his personal publishing house, so we all knew).  Susanna Hoffs is on lead vocal and rhythm guitar, Vicki Peterson on lead guitar, sister Debbi Peterson on drums and Michael Steele on bass.  Damn. it's been 30 years now, we will all miss Prince and all of his music, and I had two years on him.  This getting old is getting old!
